Indicates whether the VMS is equipped with flashing lanterns associated with the textual display area.
Number of pixels horizontally across the textual display area of the VMS.
Number of pixels vertically down the textual display area of the VMS.
Maximum number of displayable characters on a single line in the textual display area of the VMS.
Maximum number of rows of displayable characters in the textual display area of the VMS.
Indicates which legend/text code list is referenced. This may be specific to the VMS type defined by vmsTypeCode.
Maximum luminance level that is available on the textual display area of the VMS.
Maximum number of text pages which the VMS is capable of displaying sequentially.

index = 1..n
Each VMS associated with a VMS unit is referenced by its index.
Identification of the logical location (e.g. a car park, a section of road , a junction etc.) which this sign contributes to the management of.
Distance of the VMS from the logical location which this sign contributes to the management of.
Number of variable message signs contolled by this unit.
Type of fault currently being indicated for the VMS unit.
IP network address of the VMS unit.
Electronic address of VMS unit (if not IP addressable).
Indicates if the lanterns are turned on or off for the pictogram display area.
Indicates whether the automatic luminance level of the VMS for the pictogram display area is being overriden (i.e. by a level set by the instation or operator).
Luminance level that is set for the pictogram display area of the VMS. This may be set automatically by the VMS or by the instation or operator.
Indicates whether the VMS is equipped with flashing lanterns associated with the pictogram display area.
Number of pixels horizontally across the pictogram display area of the VMS.
Number of pixels vertically down the pictogram display area of the VMS.
Indicates which pictogram code list is referenced.
Owner (authority or organisation) of the VMS. This may not necessarily be the same as the authority or organisation which is controlling the VMS.
Description of how the VMS is physically mounted or deployed on the road.
Indicates the display characteristics of the specific variable message sign.
Indicates the type of VMS by code, normally country or even manufacturer specific (e.g. MS4).
Number of pictogram display areas which the VMS contains.

pageNumber = 1..n
Where multiple pages of text are defined each is referenced by its "pageNumber" and is displayed sequentially in the same display area.
The description of the VMS (possibly giving a description of its location or its normal use)
Indicates whether the VMS is usable. Note it may still be usable with minor faults.
Indicates the type of fault which is being recorded for the specified variable message sign.
Indicates if the lanterns are turned on or off for the text display area.
Indicates whether the automatic luminance level of the VMS for the text display area is being overriden (i.e. by a level set by the instation or operator).
Luminance level that is set for the text display area of the VMS. This may be set automatically by the VMS or by the instation or operator.

index = 1..n
Where different systems or authorities are concurrently requesting to set different messages on the same sign (e.g. contention between a national road authority and an urban authority) the index indicates the current display priority assigned to those messages.
Only the message with an index of "1" is actually being displayed currently. The resolution of the contention between different requestors is normally part of the VMS sub-system or instation.
The code of the pictogram from the pictogram code list (referenced in VMSPictogramDisplayCharacteristics).
Reference to a URL from where an image of the displayable pictogram can be be obtained.
Indication of whether the pictogram is flashing.
The position of the area in which the pictogram is displayed relative to the textual area of the VMS (e.g. to the left, to the right ....).
Value of distance that is displayable as part of the pictogram (e.g. for keep minimum safe distance).
Value of height that is displayable as part of the pictogram (e.g. for a vehicle height restriction).
Value of length that is displayable as part of the pictogram (e.g. for a vehicle length restriction).
Value of speed that is displayable as part of the pictogram (e.g. for a maximum speed limit).
Value of weight that is displayable as part of the pictogram (e.g. for a maximum weight restriction).
Value of width that is displayable as part of the pictogram (e.g. for a vehicle width restriction).
The identification of the traffic management plan or diversion plan with which the message is associated.
The organisation or authority which set the message currently being displayed.
Indicates whether the message has been set automatically by a system.
The reason why the sign has been set.
The reason, in terms of a high level classification, why the sign has been set.
Identifies whether the message setting is primary (explicitly requested) or is secondary (derived according to an algorthm as the result of setting other signs).
The date/time at which the sign was last set.
The authority, organisation or system which requested the setting of the message. This may be different from the authority or system which actually set the message on behalf of the requestor.
A reference to the managed situation to which the set message relates.
A reference to the situation record/element within a managed situation to which the set message relates.
Distance of the VMS from the location of the related situation record/element. If the VMS is located within the extent of the situation record/element this should be set to zero.
A free-text field containing a single displayed legend row on the specific variable message sign.
The code of the legend/text from the legend code list (referenced in VMSTextDisplayCharacteristics).
Indication of whether the page of text is flashing.
The colour of the displayable text.
One line of displayable text, each line being ordered. Each line is defined by an xml string showing text formatting tags.
Reference to a URL from where an image of the displayed legend text can be be obtained.
Type of textual information being displayed when not a specific traffic related message.

pictogramIndex = 1..n
Each pictogram associated with a VMS message is displayed in a separate area on the sign and is referenced by its "pictogramIndex".
Description of the supplementary displayable pictogram.
The code of the supplementary pictogram from the pictogram list (referenced in VMSPictogramDisplayCharacteristics).
Reference to a URL from where an image of the displayable supplementary pictogram can be be obtained.
Additional description of the supplementary pictogram.
Indication of whether the pictogram is flashing.
The position of the area in which the supplementary pictogram is displayed relative to the position of the main pictogram (e.g. below)
Container package for content model extensions. Each extension should be contained in its own package.
Relative positions of one equipment to another.
Types of general textual information displayable on a VMS.
The ways in which equipments such as VMS are mounted or deployed on the road.
Coded reasons why a message has been selected for display a the sign.
Characteristics specific to the textual display area on the VMS.
The logical location (e.g. a car park, a section of road , a junction etc.) which this sign contributes to the management of.
Details and settings of a VMS unit which may control one or more variable message signs.
Settings specific to a distinct pictogram display area on the VMS (where pictogramIndex indicates which pictogram area it relates to if there is more than one pictogram display area on the VMS).
Characteristics specific to the pictogram display area(s) on the VMS (where pictogramIndex indicates which pictogram area it relates to if there is more than one pictogram display area on the VMS).
Characteristics of the variable message sign.
A publication containing the current details and settings of one or more VMS units, each unit controlling one or more individual variable message signs.
Provides information about the variable message sign and the information currently displayed (and requested to be displayed where control of the VMS is shared).
Settings specific to a distinct text display area on the VMS.
A pictogram displayable on the VMS. Note a pictogram may comprise a main and a supplementary element.
Details of the message currently displayed on the VMS. The message may comprise one or more sequential pages of text and/or one or more simultaneously displayed pictograms .
One or more ordered lines of text (a page) that are displayed simultaneously on the VMS. Where more than one page is defined these are displayed sequentially according to their "pageNumber".
A pictogram which is supplemental to the main pictogram (i.e. displayed together with, but subordinate to the main pictogram).
